          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Indonesia joins BRICS
</h2> 
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-8-1.jpg" alt="Indonesia joins BRICS" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Indonesia has <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-01-2025-h1-1-officially-joined-the-brics" target="_blank">officially joined the BRICS</a>, becoming its tenth full member. Jakarta views membership as a step towards global collaboration and sustainable development. Brazil, the 2025 BRICS president, welcomed Indonesia, noting shared goals like reforming global governance and promoting South-South cooperation. Indonesia, the fourth most populous country, has the largest economy in Southeast Asia.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4; filter:blur(5px);">The bloc expanded last year as Iran, Egypt, Ethiopia, and the United Arab Emirates became full members. Two other candidates were <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-01-2025-h1-2-invited-but-havent-joined" target="_blank">invited but haven’t joined</a> yet: Argentina declined, and Saudi Arabia is still considering. Turkey, Azerbaijan, and Malaysia have formally applied to become members, and a few others have expressed interest. The organization was established to counterbalance the G7. The BRICS accounted for 46% of the world's population and 35% of global gross domestic product before Indonesia’s inclusion.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

